#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:314
msgid ""
"RMDs must be taken by December 31st each year. First-year RMDs can be "
"delayed until April 1st of the following year (but you'll need to take two "
"RMDs that year)."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:326
msgid "How is my RMD calculated?"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:331
msgid ""
"Your RMD is calculated by dividing your prior year-end account balance by "
"your life expectancy factor from the IRS Uniform Lifetime Table. For "
"example, if your balance was $500,000 and your factor is 26.5, your RMD "
"would be $18,868."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:336
msgid "Can I withdraw more than my RMD?"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:341
msgid ""
"Yes! The RMD is the minimum you must withdraw. You can always take more. "
"However, any excess cannot be applied to future years' RMDs. Extra "
"withdrawals will be taxed as ordinary income."
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:346
msgid "What if I have multiple IRAs?"
msgstr ""

#: Financial_Calculators/templates/financial_calculators/rmd_calculator.html:351
msgid ""
"You must calculate RMDs separately for each Traditional IRA you own. "
"However, you can take the total amount from any one or combination of your "
"IRAs. 401(k) RMDs must be taken from each account separately."
msgstr ""

