msgid "BTU Equivalent"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:803
msgid "Common Use"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:810
msgid "HVAC systems, heating/cooling"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:815
msgid "Electrical energy, utility bills"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:820
msgid "Scientific measurements, SI unit"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:825
msgid "Food energy, nutrition"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:830
msgid "Mechanical work, torque"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:845
msgid ""
"These calculations are estimates based on standard formulas and industry "
"guidelines. Actual requirements may vary based on specific building "
"characteristics, local climate variations, window orientation, ceiling "
"height, and other factors."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:851
msgid ""
"For accurate HVAC system sizing, especially for new construction or major "
"renovations, consult with a licensed HVAC contractor or engineer. They can "
"perform Manual J calculations (industry standard) that account for all "
"factors."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:857
msgid ""
"Consider factors like ceiling height (standard is 8 feet, but vaulted "
"ceilings need more BTU), window orientation (south-facing windows get more "
"sun), number and size of windows, and local building codes when making final "
"decisions."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:863
#, python-format
msgid ""
"Add 10-20%% extra capacity for safety margin, future expansion, or if your "
"home has unusual features. However, avoid oversizing by more than 20%% as it "
"can cause short-cycling, poor humidity control, and energy waste."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:869
msgid ""
"Energy efficiency improvements (better insulation, energy-efficient windows, "
"sealing air leaks) can significantly reduce BTU requirements and lower "
"energy costs. Consider these improvements before sizing your HVAC system."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:879
msgid "How many BTU do I need per square foot?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:880
msgid ""
"The standard is approximately 20 BTU per square foot, but this varies from "
"15-30 BTU/sq ft based on room type. Kitchens and attics need more (30), "
"while bathrooms need less (15). Our calculator automatically adjusts based "
"on your room type selection."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:883
msgid "What's the difference between heating and cooling BTU?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:884
#, python-format
msgid ""
"Cooling typically requires 20%% more BTU than heating because air "
"conditioning must remove both heat and humidity. The cooling load mode "
"accounts for additional factors like solar heat gain, occupants, and "
"appliances that primarily affect cooling needs."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:887
msgid "How does insulation affect BTU requirements?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:888
#, python-format
msgid ""
"Insulation quality has a significant impact. Excellent insulation can reduce "
"BTU needs by 20%%, while poor or no insulation can increase requirements by "
"50-100%%. Proper insulation is one of the most cost-effective ways to reduce "
"HVAC requirements."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:891
msgid "Should I size my system larger than calculated?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:892
#, python-format
msgid ""
"Add 10-20%% for safety margin, but avoid oversizing by more than 20%%. "
"Oversized systems short-cycle (turn on/off frequently), which reduces "
"efficiency, causes poor humidity control, and increases wear. Proper sizing "
"is more important than extra capacity."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:895
msgid "How do I convert BTU to tons for air conditioning?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:896
msgid ""
"1 ton of cooling = 12,000 BTU/hour. To convert, divide BTU by 12,000. For "
"example, 24,000 BTU = 2 tons. Most residential air conditioners are rated in "
"tons (1.5, 2, 2.5, 3, 4, 5 tons)."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:899
msgid "What is Manual J calculation?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/btu_calculator.html:900
msgid ""
"Manual J is the industry-standard method for calculating heating and cooling "
"loads. It's more detailed than our calculator, accounting for every window, "
"door, wall, and building component. For new construction or major projects, "
"a professional Manual J calculation is recommended."
msgstr ""

