#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:346
msgid "Why 5252?"
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:348
msgid ""
"The constant 5252 in the horsepower formula comes from unit conversions. One "
"horsepower is defined as 550 foot-pounds per second. To convert RPM to "
"revolutions per second, we divide by 60. To convert to foot-pounds per "
"minute, we multiply by 60. The calculation: (550 ft-lb/s × 60 s/min) / (2π "
"rad/rev) = 5252. This constant ensures that horsepower and torque curves "
"intersect at 5252 RPM when plotted on the same graph."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:355
msgid "All torque and power values must be greater than zero."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:356
msgid "RPM must be between 1 and 50,000 for valid calculations."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:357
msgid ""
"The formula HP = (Torque × RPM) / 5252 is valid for rotational power "
"calculations."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:358
msgid "Torque can be entered in foot-pounds (ft-lb) or Newton-meters (N⋅m)."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:359
msgid "Power can be converted between HP, kW, and watts."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:361
msgid ""
"The constant 5252 is specific to the relationship between HP, torque (in ft-"
"lb), and RPM."
msgstr ""

#: Other_Calculators/templates/other_calculators/horsepower_calculator.html:362
msgid ""
"For metric calculations, torque in N⋅m is automatically converted to ft-lb "
"for the formula."
msgstr ""

